# Implicit Wait in Selenium Python

1️⃣ Why Waits Are Needed
Modern web applications use AJAX and dynamic loading.
This means:
    1. When a webpage loads , some elements appear later
    2. Selenium may try to find elements before it loads

If the element not available in the DOM (Document Object Model) , Selenium throws an exceptions like:
    1. NoSuchElementException
    2. ElementNotVisibleException
To handle this issue , selenium provides Waits.

2️⃣ Types of Waits in Selenium
Selenium provides two types of waits:
    1. Implicit Wait
    2. Explicit Wait
This section explains Implicit Wait.

3️⃣ What is Implicit Wait?
Implicit wait tells selenium to wait for a certain amount of time while searching for elements.
If the element is not immediately available , Selenium:
    1. Keeps checking the DOM
    2. Until the element appears
    3. or the maximum time appears

4️⃣ Default Behavior
By Default:
    Implicit Wait = 0 seconds
This means:
    1. Selenium does not wait
    2. if element not found -> exception occurs immediately

5️⃣ Syntax
    driver.implicitly_wait(time_in_seconds)

    Parameter & meaning
    -------------------
    driver -> WebDriver Instance
    time_in_seconds -> Maximum time selenium will wait

    Example
    -------
    driver.implcitly_wait(10)
Selenium will wait up to 10 seconds to find elements.

6️⃣ Important Characteristics
    1. Applied globally
    2. Applies to all elements in the script
    3. Set only once
    4. Active during the entire WebDriver session

    Example:
        driver=WebDriver.FireFox()
        driver.implicitly_wait(10)
    
Now every element search will wait up to 10 seconds

7️⃣ Example 1 – Basic Implicit Wait

from selenium import webdriver
from selenium.common import By
driver=webdriver.FireFox()
driver.implicitly_wait(10)
driver.get("http://somedomain/url_that_delays_loading")
myDynamicElement=driver.find_element(By.ID , "myDynamicElement")

    Explanation
    -----------
    1. selenium opens the browser
    2. Implicit wait is set to 10 seconds
    3. Selenium tries to find element myDynamicElement
    4. If the element appears within 10 seconds , selenium continues
    5. if not found -> exception occurs

8️⃣ Example 2 – Real Website Example

from selenium import webdriver
from selenium.common import By

driver=WebDriver.FireFox()
driver.implcitly_wait(10)
driver.get("https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/")
element=driver.find_element(By.LINK_TEXT , "Courses")
element.click()
driver.quit()

    Step-by-Step
    ------------
    1. Browser opens GeekGorGeeks website
    2. Selenium waits up to 10 seconds
    3. It searches for Courses link
    4. When element appears -> Selenium clicks it
    5. Browser navigates to Courses Page

9️⃣ How Implicit Wait Works Internally
    Example
    driver.implicitly_wait(10)

    selenium will:
    0 sec -> check element
    1 sec -> check
    2 sec -> check
    3 sec -> check
    .
    .
    10 sec -> check

If the element appears earlier -> Selenium continues immediately.

🔟 Advantages of Implicit Wait
    1. Simply to use
    2. Works globally
    3. Reduce element-not-found errors
    4. Handles small delays in page loading

11️⃣ Limitations of Implicit Wait
❌ Applies to all elements even when not required
❌ Less control compared to Explicit Wait
❌ Not ideal for complex dynamic elements

12️⃣ Real-Life Example
Imagine you are waiting for a friend.
Implicit wait means:
    I will wait for my friend for 10 minutes , checking continueously.

If your friend arrives in 3 minutes , you leave immediately.
If not -> you stop waiting for 10 mins. 
